node.text:
Now that the new year is here I feel it’s important to share this with you so can all be aware of the abuse that these beautiful animals go through so people can take some cute photos during their vacation. .
hope this Video🎥 can open Your eyes👀 a bit and give you a perspective on "Animal Interaction“ you might never had before!🤷🏼‍♂️ It‘s all up to US (Humans) if we accept things like this or not! If we support these things or not! 😓
•
Please SHARE this Video and help us shine a light on this serious global🌍 problem‼️Together we CAN END Animal Cruelty & Slavery🐾⛓
•
Also tag at least 3 Friends in the comments so we can spread this message. .
.
Thank you @dean.schneider for all the work you’re doing!

node.text:
Did you know that Malaysia has islands with the clearest water similar to Maldives? Mabul is a small island off the south-eastern coast of Sabah in Malaysia. The island has been a fishing village since the 1970s. In the 1990s, it first became popular to divers due to its proximity to Sipadan island

📍 Mabul Island in Malaysia 
📷 @lynnl0107

node.text:
Morelet's tree frog is a species of leaf frog in the family Phyllomedusidae. It is found in Belize, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, and Mexico. They have also been called black-eyed leaf frog and popeye hyla. 

If you’re the owner of this video please DM me @ericdamier

node.text:
Imagine having this job? Located in Amsterdam airport, it’s Actually A 24-Hour Performance Art Piece. a truly unique way of ensuring travellers make it to the gate on time.

The Schipol Clock hangs 3m above the ground and and appears to be home to a permanent resident in the form of a man in uniform who painstakingly paints the time minute-by-minute. 

Don’t let it fool you though — it’s actually just a video on loop, and it’s not the first of its kind. Back in 2009, the clock’s Dutch designer, Maarten Baas, launched the series at the Milan Furniture Fair with Sweepers, in which two men sweep trash into a living time clock for 12 hours straight. After that came Analog Digital, which shows a man painting over and wiping clean panels on a glass screen of a standard digital clock, which was later developed into an app.

Each project, including the newest addition at Amsterdam’s airport, took 12 time-consuming hours to film.
